180	\section{Sheaf cohomology with \(k\)-module coefficients}
181	\label{sec:HModule}
182	
183	The abstract cohomology API is formulated for sheaves of abelian groups. To obtain a \(k\)-vector-space structure on \(H^n(C, \mathcal O_C)\), we build a parallel sheaf cohomology valued in \(k\)-modules. The sheaf category of \(k\)-modules already has \(\Ext\) (Theorem~REF), and \(\Ext\) groups in any \(k\)-linear abelian category carry a canonical \(k\)-module structure.
184	
185	\begin{definition}\leanok
186	[Sheaf cohomology with \(k\)-module coefficients]
187	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule}
188	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule}
189	  
190	  Let \(k\) be a field, \(C\) a Grothendieck site admitting sheafification of \(k\)-modules and \(\Ext\). For a sheaf \(F\) of \(k\)-modules and \(n \in \mathbb N\), define the \(k\)-module-valued sheaf cohomology
191	  \[
192	    H^n_{\Module}(F) \;:=\; \Ext^n\bigl(\text{constant sheaf at }k,\; F\bigr).
193	  \]
194	  This automatically carries a \(k\)-module structure.
195	\end{definition}
196	
197	\begin{remark}[Lean implementation]
198	  The declaration uses a reducible wrapper (`abbrev` rather than `def`) so that instance synthesis sees through to the underlying \(\Ext\) group and finds both the \(k\)-module and abelian-group structures automatically. Under a non-reducible wrapper, `Module.finrank` would fail to typecheck.
199	\end{remark}
